Force the LoongArch glibc dynamic linker path to the "old world" location
used by Loongnix 20 (DaoXiangHu) and other pre-upstream LoongArch distros.

Upstream GCC emits "/lib64/ld-linux-loongarch-lp64d.so.1" (or similar,
parameterised by ABI_GRLEN_SPEC / ABI_SPEC). Loongnix 20 binaries hard-coded
the legacy path "/lib64/ld.so.1" — leftover from the pre-upstream toolchain
that Loongson shipped before the kernel + glibc merge.

Without this patch, binaries produced by an upstream-style GCC 14 fail at
load time on Loongnix 20 with "No such file or directory" (the kernel
can't find the requested interpreter), even though the binary is on disk.

This patch is intentionally minimal — it only changes the glibc dynamic
linker macro; everything else (multilib spec, ld.so search dirs in glibc
itself) is fine because glibc 2.28 on the target is happy to be loaded as
/lib64/ld.so.1.

After applying this patch, rebuild GCC; verify with:
  $ loongarch64-linux-gnu-gcc -O2 hello.c -o hello
  $ readelf -l hello | grep INTERP
  [Requesting program interpreter: /lib64/ld.so.1]

Applies cleanly to GCC 14.2.0 release tarball.

--- a/gcc/config/loongarch/gnu-user.h
+++ b/gcc/config/loongarch/gnu-user.h
@@ -22,7 +22,7 @@ along with GCC; see the file COPYING3.  If not see

 #undef GLIBC_DYNAMIC_LINKER
 #define GLIBC_DYNAMIC_LINKER \
-  "/lib" ABI_GRLEN_SPEC "/ld-linux-loongarch-" ABI_SPEC ".so.1"
+  "/lib64/ld.so.1"

 #undef MUSL_DYNAMIC_LINKER
 #define MUSL_DYNAMIC_LINKER \
